Alternatively, luanam is connected with Gr. λούω, λο(ϝ)έ-σαι ‘to bathe, wash (the body)’, Lat. lavō, lavere ‘to wash, bathe’, etc. and thus identified with Arm. loganam ‘to bathe’, see NHB 1: 893c; Hübschmann 1897: 454 (hesitantly); HAB 2: 300b with more references; Klingenschmitt 1982: 116-117; Clackson 1994: 44. For the alternation -u- : -og- cf. č‘uem vs. č‘og- ‘to go, set off’ (q.v.).

The verbs 'to go' and 'to come' in the Brittonic languages have suppletive paradigms. The finite forms ar based on the stems a- < *ag- < *h₂eg̑- 'to drive' and el- < *pelh₂- 'to approach'. In the paradigm of 'to go', these forms are used uncompounded, while in the paradigm of 'to come', they contain the preverb *tu-. In Middle Welsh, some Imoerative forms are based on *ret-e/o- <*ret- 'to run'. The verbal nouns of 'to come' Welsh mynet, Breton monet originate from PIE *menH- 'to step, to stamp' (?). The verbal noun of 'to go', Breton donet contains the same root prefixed with *tu-, i.e. *de-vonet, cf. also Old Breton diminet. The Welsh verbal noun dyfod 'to come' contains *tu- + bod 'to be' based on PIE *bʰweh₂- 'to become, to grow'.

A general problem: If a language forms productively a verb from a borrowed noun, this verb would not be considered as a loan word. With regard to contaff, however, it is impossible to know if the verb or the noun have been borrowed first, i.e. if Deshayes' hypothesis cited below is correct. Note, that there is a corresponding verb in Cornish. Early borrowing in South-West-British or independent borrowings?

From Ancient Greek ποδίον, diminutive of ποῦς.

No perfect cognates in Irish and British, cf. fn. 40: According to Watkins, Trivium 1 (1966), 106 in Irish with generalized full grade from the nominative singular, while Welsh dyw is based on the genitive singular *diw-és.
The Brittonic words originate from PIE *prō-ko- (no exact cognates; Avestan, Old Church Slavonic and Latin have *pro-ko-).
From Proto-Celtic *klad-o- 'dig, bury', cf. PIE *kelh₂- 'hit, break' (LIV² 350, IEW 546f.).

Welsh cau 'hollow' is also borrowed from Latin cavus, this loan word might originate from the Brittonic period >> check.
Generally regarded as a Loan word, a verb derived productively from a native adjective would according to Matasovic be possible.
Verb based on Proto-Celtic *fib-o- 'to drink', cf. PIE *peh₃(i̯)- 'to drink' (LIV² 462f.).
Probaby from Proto-Celtic *lukato-, from the PIE root *lewk- 'to become bright' (LIV 438).
From Proto-Celtic *kʷello- 'far', cf. PIE *kʷel- 'to turn' (IEW 640; note that this root is reconstructed as *kʷelh₁- in LIV 386). Matasović considers this etymology as rather speculative.
From Proto-Celtic *obnu- or *obno- 'fear' < PIE *h₁ogʷno- or *h₁ogʷnu-, cf. PIE *h₁egʷ- (not in LIV).
From Latin pluma 'feather(s)'. Old borrowing in Insular Celtic, cf. Old Irish clum, cluim, Welsh plum.
Although Deshayes' suggestion is theoretically possible, it is not convincing. The supposed Celtic *kʷluma has no cognate outside Celtic, while Latin pluma does, cf. de Vaan (474).
From Ancient κρατέω 'be strong, have power; rule; lay hold of'
Singular stem κέρατο remodelled on the basis of the plural κέρατα.
Consists of the negator nep and meur 'big'.
Cf. Old Breton nepot. From Proto-Celtic *ne-kwāt-.
From Proto-Celtic *tefnet- 'fire', cogante with other words for 'warm' and 'heat' based on PIE *tep- 'to be warm, to be hot' (LIV 629).
Based on Proto-Celtic *blātu- 'flower', cf. PIE *bleh₃- 'to blossom, to flower' (LIV 88).
From Proto-Celtic *flāno- 'full' < PIE *pl̥h₁no- 'full' (IEW 799), cf. *pleh₁- 'to fill up, to become full' (LIV² 482).

Welsh rhoddi < *ro-dī- (PIE *dʰeh₁- 'to place, to put') does not belong to the same cognate class as Middle Welsh roaf, roi, Middle Breton reiff and Middle Cornish ry. These verbs have lost an intervocalic -g- and belong to Old Irish rogaid*, ·rogai* (*rugaid, *·rugai 'to strech out' DIL 510/R89, LEIA R-39).
From Proto-Celtic *gʷeltā ‘grass’. PIE root problematic, as *gʷʰel- 'to graze' does not exist.
Greek γόνατο has been remodeled on the basis of the Ancient Greek oblique stem (G.sg. γόνατος).
From Ancient Greek ποδίον, diminutive of ποῦς 'foot'.
With lexical contamination of initial consonant cluster. φθ- > ψ- from ψύλλα 'flea'
Vocalism restored in Standard Modern Greek from katharevousa form νέος (dialectal νιος).
Stem remodelled as an a-stem on basis of Ancient Greek A.sg. νύκτα.
Stem ένα- remodelled from oblique stem (Ancient Greek A.sg. masculine ἕνα)
Probably from Proto-Celtic *emem, the reduplicated acc. sg. of the PIE pronominal stem *(h₁)e/i-.
Cognate coding needs to be checked.
From *swī(s) which reflects the PIE acc. 2 pl. *us-we.
Andriotis's proposed etymology is one of the different proposals listed in the cognate coding.  (Cognate coding needs sorting out.)

Middle Cornish ty, te and Old South-West British ti, te /tɪ/ < Late Proto-British *tɨ < Proto-British *ti. Old Welsh and Middle Welsh ti reflect Late Proto-British *ti < *tī. The attested form can be generated from Proto-Celtic *tū, *tu in more than one way. The Proto-Celtic nom. sg. *tū became Proto-British *tȳ < *tī, while the Proto-Cletic acc. sg. *te became *ti. Of these forms, Old Welsh generalized the former variant, Old South-West British the latter.

Middle Cornish ty, te and Old South-West British ti, te /tɪ/ < Late Proto-British *tɨ < Proto-British *ti. Old Welsh and Middle Welsh ti reflect Late Proto-British *ti < *tī. The attested form can be generated from Proto-Celtic *tū, *tu in more than one way. The Proto-Celtic nom. sg. *tū became Proto-British *tȳ < *tī, while the Proto-Celtic acc. sg. *te became *ti. Of these forms, Old Welsh generalized the former variant, Old South-West British the latter.

Middle Cornish ty, te and Old South-West British ti, te /tɪ/ < Late Proto-British *tɨ < Proto-British *ti. Old Welsh and Middle Welsh ti reflect Late Proto-British *ti < *tī. The attested form can be generated from Proto-Celtic *tū, *tu in more than one way. The Proto-Celtic nom. sg. *tū became Proto-British *tȳ < *tī, while the Proto-Celtic acc. sg. *te became *ti. Of these forms, Old Welsh generalized the former variant, Old South-West British the latter.
From Proto-Celtic *klus-i- 'to hear', cf. PIE *k̑lews- 'to hear, to listen' (LIV 336).
Cognate with Old Irish aitheach 'vassal, peasant', both from Proto-Celtic *fotiko- 'head of the household' < PIE *potiko-.
From Proto-Celtic *glūnos- 'knee'. Origin from PIE *gónu- is beyond doubt, although some soundchanges in Celtic are hard to understand.

Compound of Old Breton guid-, Middle Breton gouz- 'to know' and -but, the verbal noun of 'to be'. The finite forms are made up of the respective tenses of 'to be' attached to guid-/gouz-. Cognate verbs in Cornish and Welsh.
Modern Greek φτύνω from Ancient Greek πτύω with re-characterisation of the present stem as a nasal-present.
Originally 'fresh', with meaning transferred from earlier collocation νῆρον ὕδωρ 'fresh water'
From Ancient (koiné) Greek ἡμεῖς. Replacement of initial */i/ <η> with /e/ analogical within the pronominal system.
From Proto-Celtic *dol-V-, cf. PIE *dʰelh₁- 'to ooze out, to pullulate' (LIV 132).

From Proto-Celtic *garrV- 'calf of the leg, shank' with cognates in Oir. gairr (i m or t) 'calf of the leg', MW garr m. 'leg, shank, ham, thigh', Co. gar 'leg' and Gaulish *garra > OFr. gare 'leg'. Matasović suggests to derive these forms from the PIE word for 'hand' (PIE *ghesr > Hitt. kissar, Gr. kheir, IEW 447) and gives two possible developments that would yield the Celtic forms regularly. The semantic development was then 'hand, arm'> 'limb'> '(calf of the) leg'.

From Proto-Celtic *luwā 'louse', cf. PIE *lewH- 'louse' (IEW 692).
The PCelt. form is compatible with both PIE *lowHo- > *luwo-,
and with PIE *luHo- > *luwo-.
From Proto-Celtic *wĭro- 'man' < PIE: *wiHro- 'man' (IEW 1177). With short *ĭ in Celtic.

The origin of cals is obscure. It may be the same word as Modern Breton kalz 'heap': ur c'hals teil 'a dunghill'. In fact, Modern Breton ur c'halz is sometimes used instead of kalz itself: eur c'halz ac'hanomp 'many of us'.
From Proto-Celtic *melino- 'yellow', based on *meli- 'honey'. The original meaning was 'honey-colored'.
From Proto-Celtic *kai̯to- 'wood' < PIE *kai̯to- 'wood, field' (IEW 521). Cognate set limited to Celtic and Germanic and ultimately perhaps a substratum word.
OIr. cét-, ceta- preverb, Old Welsh preposition cant 'with' < *km̥-th₂, an adverbial formation of 1. *ko, 1. kóm 'together, with, at'

From Proto-Celtic *awelā 'breeze, wind', cf. PIE *h₂uh₁-el- (IEW 81ff.). Neuter l-stem, probably with nom. sg. *h₂ewh₁-l, gen. sg. *h₁uh₂-el-s. 
Cognate with Gr. áella 'stormwind'.
From Proto-Celtic *flitano- 'broad'< *pl̥th₂-no- 'broad' (IEW 806,833, *pleth₂- 'to become broad, to spread' LIV² 486).

From Proto-Celtic *kʷēs 'who' < PIE *kʷe/o-i̯- 'who, what' (IEW 635).
While OW pui, MW pwy show the regular outcome, in Middle Breton and Cornish a metathesis *wy > yw took place.

From Old British pi, pe, which can be connected with OIr. cía, ce, ci e.g. cía chruth 'what way?'. However not identical with Welsh pa, which may reflect an old oblique case form or an adverb used as an oblique case form.

From Old British pi, pe, which can be connected with OIr. cía, ce, ci e.g. cía chruth 'what way?'. However not identical with Welsh pa, which may reflect an old oblique case form or an adverb used as an oblique case form.

Old British pi, pe can be connected with OIr. cía, ce, ci e.g. cía chruth 'what way?'. It is however not identical with Welsh pa, which may reflect an old oblique case form or an adverb used as an oblique case form. It is tempting to compare pa with Oir. co- 'how'? and reconstruct an adverbial interrogative stem *kʷa-. Late Proto-British *pa was lost in South-West-British and survived only in Welsh, where it was confused with *pɨ > OW pi, MW py.
First attested in the Catholicon. From Old French *coffe, variant of coffre (1175) from Vulgar Latin *cophinum of Greek origin.
First attested in the Cathilicon (1499). It has been assumed to originate from Latin locusta 'grasshopper' but rather of unknown origin.

The history of OCS ѫтроба, SC utroba, M утроба on the one hand, and of B вътрешности, R внутренности, P wnętrzności, Sv vnútornosti, C vnitřnosti on the other hand is a bit complicated. They are not direct cognates (for Proto Slavic I would assume two different roots here) but deeply they share a common root.

Related to Middle Breton croc adj. 'attached, taken', m. 'fang, hook, efford' from Old French croc (end of 12th cent.) from Scandinavian krôkr.
Croc and creguiff are both first attested in the Catholicon (1499).
First attested in the Catholicon (1499). Cognate with Welsh wybr 'heaven', wybren 'firmament', Cornish ebren 'firmament'. From Proto-Brittonic (*ko(m)-) + *oepr (what is this)?

First attested in the Catholicon (1499). Related to the noun cont 'count, number, account, mention' (). Borrowed from Old French conte noun 'count' (1080) and conter 'to count, to calculate', both from Latin computare.

Middle Breton niveraff is first attested in the Catholicon (1499). It can be analyzed as a denominal verb. The basis niver 'number' is borrowed from Latin numerus. This borrowing took place early, cf. Old Breton nimer 'number'. Middle Breton niveraff thus is either inherited from Old Breton or formed productively from niver.
From Latin cavus like Welsh cau.
First attested in the Catholicon (1499). Cf. Middle Cornish lôs 'dirty, miserable' and Old French los 'miserable, mean, teasing'. Origin unknown.
First attesteed in the Catholicon. Common Brittonic (thus pre-Middle Breton) borrowing (+ Irish) from Latin siccus.
Like Welsh twn 'cut, broken' from VLat. *tondere.
From Old Breton deprim < *di- + prim. The second element corresponds to Irish crim- in crimóg 'morsel' (where attested? Neither in eDIL nor in Ó Dónaill).

Attested in the Catholicon (1499). (Deshayes gives 1396 as date of first attestation. What source is this?)
Borrowed from Old French lard, lart (12th cent.) < Latin laridum 'fat'.
Based on kann 'white' from Proto-Celtic *kando-. The original meaning of the verb is 'to bleach laundry (by beating)' > 'to beat'.
First attested in the Catholicon (1499). Pre-Middle Breton loan-word from Latin piscis.

First attested in the Catholicon (1499), cf. the cognate noun flod 'flood, tide; fleet' (beginning of 16th cent.). The latter is borrowed from Old French flot (1175) from Frankish *flôt 'flood' and Skandinavian floti 'raft'.
From Old French brume 'winter' (1260) from Latin bruma 'winter'.
First attested in the Catholicon (1499). Verb based on Proto-Celtic *danto-, cf. Middle Breton dant (1499).
First attested in the Catholicon (1499). Pre-Middle Breton borrowing. Common Brittonic borrowing from Vulgar Latin *virdis from Latin viridis.
First attested in the manuscript version of the Catholicon (1464). Borrowed from Old French coraille 'guts, intestines' (1160) based on Latin cor 'heart'.
First attested in the Catholicon (1499). Borrowed from Latin ponderis 'of weight'.
First attested in the Catholicon (1499). Cognate with the noun sco m. 'blow, clash' (1732) of unknown origin.

Based on Protoo-Celtic *delg-o- 'hold, contain', cf. MW daly, dala 'hold', 
OBret. delgim, delgu [Is Pres.] (Banassac) and perhaps Olr. coindelg 'contract, comparison' < *kom-delgo- (cf. also W cynnal 'maintain'); a deverbal nominal stem (*delgo-) is probably preserved in OBret. dalg (MoBret. dalc'h) 'maintenance, tenure'. PIE connection not clear, check IEW 197.
First attested in the Doctrinal (1622). Denominative verb from the Old French noun chace 'hunt' (12th cent.), which developed into the suppletive plural for ki 'dog'.
Only the base is borrowed, not the whole verb.

Verb based on the Proto-Celtic noun *selgā 'hunt', cf. PIE *selg̑- 'send away, set loose' (LIV² 528-29, IEW 900f.). Breton has two verbs from this base: the simplex helc'hiñ and the compound (h)emholc'h, (h)emolc'hiñ from *ambi-selg-o-.
Cites only the simplex verb helc'hiñ 'to chase, to exhaust, to tire out'.
First attested in the Catholicon (1499). No cognates outside Breton, orogin unknown.
Favereau cites Cornish scorn and Old French sorne (Ernault). CHECK

From Proto-Celtic *su̯ar-yo- 'to laugh' < PIE *swer- 'sound, make a sound' (IEW 1049f.). "The attribution of these Celtic forms to the PIE root *swer- is semantically difficult, but possible (see KPV 609). PCelt. *swar-yo- continues the zero-grade of the root, PIE *su̯r̥-i̯o-."
Cognate with Cornish and Welsh. Verb related to the noun gourwez m., compound of gour- and Breton gwez, Corn. gweth, W gwedd 'aspect, form'.
Verb based on bew ad. 'livin, alive' < Proto-Celtic *biu̯o-, cf. PIE *gʷi̯eh₃- 'to live', cf. Matasović (2009: 67).
From Proto-Celtic *kīkā 'breast'. In Brittonic the meaing is 'meat', but the meaning of Mir. cich [a f] 'breast' is probably the original one. Also in Gaul. Cic-ollus, PN. Popular expressive word.

From Proto-Celtic *lugrā- 'moon', PIE *leu̯g- 'to bend, twist' (IEW 685f., LIV 416). Presupposes that the young moon was denoted as 'bent'. The connection with *leu̯k- 'to shine' (IEW 690) is impossible for phonological reasons as this root contains *k, not *g.

From Proto-Celtic *lugrā- 'moon', PIE *leu̯g- 'to bend, twist' (IEW 685f., LIV 416). Presupposes that the young moon was denoted as 'bent'. The connection with *leu̯k- 'to shine' (IEW 690) is impossible for phonological reasons as this root contains *k, not *g.

From Proto-Celtic *mamm(i̯)ā 'mother, nanny', cf. PIE: *mam(m)a 'mommy' (IEW 694). Cognate with Olr. muimme (i̯ā, f.) 'nurse, fostermother'.
"These forms are from the children's language, while the 'formal'
word for 'mother' is preserved in Olr. mathir. The fact that the nursery word *mamma usually does not denote the biological mother is explained by the Celtic custom of fosterage (children are raised by foster-parents, with whom they develop an intimate relationship)."

From Proto-Celtic *genu- 'jaw' < PIE: *g̑enu- 'jaw' (IEW 381).
The singular of this word is reflected in OIr. gin u m. 'mouth' and in the Brittonic words for 'cheek', MW gen f.'cheek', OBret. gen gl. maxilla, MBret. guen, MoBret. gen f. 'cheek'.
The Breton word for 'mouth' is based on the plural Proto-Celtic *genou̯es.
From Proto-Celtic *bek(k)o- 'beak, snout', probably an expressive word comparable to Lat. bucca 'mouth'. Cf. Gaul. beccus (Suetonius), *bekko- > Fr. bec.

From Proto-Celtic *anman 'name', cf. PIE *h₃nomn̥ 'name' (IEW 321). 
The Celtic forms are derived from the oblique cases of the PIE
word for 'name', i.e. from *h₃nmen-, just like, e.g., the Slavic forms (cf. Russ. imja).
Discusses the different reconstructions of the PIE word.
Cf. Old Breton strit. From Latin strictus. Pre-Middle Breton loan-word.
From Proto-Celtic *angu- 'narrow' < PIE *h₂emg̑ʰ- 'narrow' (NIL 301). Compounds: *kom-angu- 'narrow' in Oir. cumung, MW eyf-yng, *exs-angu- 'not narrow' in MW ehang 'broad'.
First attested in the Catholicon. Brittonic borrowing (Breton, Welsh) from Latin tostus 'grilled, burned'.
From PIE *nó-h₁ 'not', based on the PIE negator *nó.

From Proto-Celtic *kotto- 'old'. 
"According to Sims-Williams (2006: 67) Cat. cot 'hill', Sp. cueto are from the Gaulish reflex of this word. The semantic development was presumably from 'old' to 'curved, humpbacked hillock'. In any case, these words are probably of non-IE origin."
Cf. Old Breton guari, huari, Middle Breton hoari, Modern Breton c'hoari m. 'game' from Proto-Celtic *su̯er-o-. Cognates in Cornish and Welsh.

From Proto-Celtic *oi̯no- 'one' < PIE *h₃ei̯-no- 'one' (IEW 28lff.).
Matasivić assumed the derivative *oi̯nano- 'alone, personally' to underly OIr. oentin and MBret. unan, onan, and W hunan (with secondary h-).

Middle Breton all from Proto-Celtic *alyo- 'other' < PIE *h₂eli̯o- 'other' (IEW 25f.). Middle Breton arall from Proto-Celtic *alal(i)i̯o- 'another, other' (reduplicated, intensive). *arali̯o- is a dissimilated form.
First attested in the Catholicon (1499). A Common Brittonic (and Irish) borrowing von Latin tendere 'to stretch, to direct'.
An inherited word based on PIE *ten- 'to stretch, to span' may have mixed up with a Latin borrowing.
From Old Breton puls 'space in time'. Like Cornish pols 'heartbeat, moment' from Latin pulsus 'pulse'.
See etymological notes in cognate coding.

First attested in the Catholicon (1499). Cf. bou(n)t m. 'thrust, push' and f. 'shoot, bud, cutting'. Borrowed from Old French boute < bot 'blow, ' (1160), bouter 'to collide, to clash, to push' (1190).

Cf. Proto-Celtic *rextu- 'rule, law' < PIE *h₃reg̑-tu-, root *h₃reg̑- 'to straighten, to stretch' (LIV 304f.).
In the following nouns: Oir. recht (u m.), MW reyth, ModW raith f. 'law, sermon, jury, verdict', MBret. rez, reiz 'law, rule, arrangement', MoBret. reizh m., Co. ryth 'sex, kind', Gaul. Rextu-genos PN, Celtib. retu-keno (Gen s, PN] (Bottorita III). All these nouns are used as adjectives as well. 
Cognate with Proto-Celtic *reg-o- 'extend, stretch'.

The adjectives mir. recht 'just, righteous', MW reizh, Middle Breton rez 'just, right' are listed by many handbooks together with the nouns and reconstructed as Proto-Celtic *rex-tu-. A there is a broad cross-linguistic evidence for a to-adjective, the underlying Proto-Celtic form may be rather *rexto-, which became homonymous with the cognate nouns in Brittonic.
From Proto-Celtic *abon- 'river' < *h₂ep-h₃on- 'river' (IEW 1: in IEW only the evidence. Lit. concerning the reconstruction see NIL 311 and fn. 15).
From Proto-Celtic *sentu- 'path', cf. PIE *sent- 'head for, go' (IEW 908); PIE *sent- 'to go' >> 'to perceive' (LIV 533).

From Proto-Celtic *u̯ridā 'root', PIE *u̯re(h₂)d- 'root' (IEW 1167).
"The Brittonic words presuppose *wridā (Breton), or *wradi- (Welsh). The form *wradi- presumably has the secondary full grade of the root instead of the expected *wredi-."

There are no arguments to sustain Deshayes' hypothesis. A common Brittonic borrowing from Latin would be equally possible.
Borrowing probably pre-Middle Breton.
Borrowed from Old French roont (1155) < Latin rotundum.

From Proto-Celtic *krundi- 'round, compact'
Matasović assumed a relation with *krumbo- 'round, compact', cf. Mod. Bret. kromm 'curved'. In this case, *krundi- may originate from *krum-di-. Both *krundi- and *krumbo- may be loanwords from some non-IE language.

From Proto-Celtic *krumbo- 'round, curved' and thus no perfect cognate with Middle Breton crenn, ModBr. krenn from Proto Celtic *krundi- 'round, compact'. According to Matasović *krundi- could originate from *krum-di- and thus possesses a different suffix. Both *krundi- and *krumbo- may be loanwords from some non-IE language.

Verb based on Proto-Celtic *tara-u̯o- 'hit, strike', PIE *terh₁- 'to drill, to rub' (IEW 1072, LIV 632) . Cognate with MW taraw, taro, (GPC trawaf[Pres 1 s]), OBret. toreusit gl. atriuit, MBret. tarauat 'rub, use', MoBret.
tarawad.
First attested in the Catholicon (1499), cf. the noun Modern Breton frot m. 'rub, friction'. Borrowed from French frotter and the corresponding deverbal noun.

From Proto-Celtic *salano- 'salt', cf. PIE *seh₂1- 'salt'. gen.sg. *sh₂1-os (IEW 878). The Irish and British forms cannot derived from a single proto-form. Old Irish salann points to a PIE derived stem *sh₂l-Hno- > PCelt. salano-, while the British words have another suffix, i.e. Proto-Celtic *saleno- < *sh₂l-eno-.

Brittonic (Welsh traeth, Corn. trait, Mbr. trez 'Sand') and Goidelic (OIr. tracht 'shore, bank') loanword from Latin tractus 'drawing, trail track'. Loth, Les mots latins dans les langues brittoniques 1892, s.v. traeth considers these word as Celtic however.

The analysis as a loanword is less probable if one considers that the underlying root is well represented in Insular Celtic (PIE *treHgʰ- / *treHg̑ʰ- or *tragʰ- / *trag̑ʰ- 'to drain off, to ebb away', cf. Schumacher 2004, 635-36) and that there are nouns from this root belonging to the same semantic field: Old Breton tre, MW trei m. 'ebbtide', Old Irish tráig 'i, m/f' 'ebbtide, beach' < Proto-Brit. *trăgi̯o-. The word for sand could thus originate from an inherited tu-stem cognate with Latin tractus, i.e. Proto-Celtic *traxtus.

Verb based on Proto-Celtic *lab(a)ro- 'eloquent, talkative'. Further cognates unclear. "These Celtic words may have been onomatopoetic in origin; the connection with ME flappen 'hit' suggested by IEW (831) is a mere possibility (if this is correct, the PCelt. form of the root was *f1ab-), cf. also Germ. labern 'babble'."

Does not belong here, cf. LIV 601 p. 601: PIE *(s)teu̯d- 'to beat': Gothic stautan 'to push'. 
Not the Swadesh term.

The root is most typical for plural. However, it is used also in singular but it is much less frequent than the alternative 'góle' and it has a defective inflection (only nominative and accusative). So for the singular (which is needed here) it is rather marginal.
It is often described as an old loanword from Germanic (cf. German 'Glas'). However, it is very disputable. Vasmer and ESSJa describe the word as original.
Refers to fight/dogfight without intention to kill someone or make serious injuries.
It can be related to 'ako' but it is not obvious.
It is very frequently used by native speakers in their dialectal speech.
Most likely an irregular caressing derivative from 'mati'.
Most likely an irregular caressing derivative from 'mati'.
Most likely an irregular caressing derivative from 'mati'.
S.v. φέβομαι.  φοβέω (active) φοβέομαι (middle) is a causative/iterative stem < *bʰogʷ-éi̯e/o-.
Uncertain (e.g., the vocalism is phonetically problematic).

From Proto-Celtic *mori- 'sea', PIE: *mori 'sea, standing water' (IEW 748).
Matasović: "W mor cannot be directly from *mori, since this would have given
**myr."

From Proto-Celtic *mori- 'sea', PIE: *mori 'sea, standing water' (IEW 748).
Matasović: "W mor cannot be directly from *mori, since this would have given
**myr."

Proto-Celtic *li-mo/ā- 'sharp' (Adj.) ?

Denominal verb
Proto-Celtic *lim-ā- 'sharpen, polish'
GOlD: MIr.limaid 'sharpens, polishes'; limsat [3p Pret.]
W: MW llymhau 'sharpen, whet, quicken'
BRET: OBret. lemhaam gl. acuo, MBret. lemaff, MoBret. lemmafi
ETYM: These words are most probably related to Lat. līma 'carpenter's
file', OHG slim 'mud, slime', silman 'make smooth', etc. The PIE root would be *(s)ley- (IEW 663), with the suffix *-mo- in Italic, Germanic, and Celtic. However, the length in aIr. limaid is unexpected (but cf. the short vowel in 3 pi. Pret. limsat).
REF: GPC II: 2271, DGVB 239, Deshayes 2003: 458.
Not universally accepted, though; some scholars find the development of initial PIE labiovelar problematic (cf. Martirosyan 2010:299).
Khot. r rather than l appears to point to a preform without *d, probably in analogy to an ancient d-less nom.-acc.sg. *zār.
Development ū- < *apa- not entirely clear (I'd reather expect au-/o-). Maybe from *uda-, contra Bailey?
Metathesis (rotation) of consonants vs. īranian *marwi-; cf. also byform in valmīka- 'ants' heap'.

From Proto-Celtic *kan-o- 'to sing', PIE *kan- 'to sing' (IEW 525f., LIV²  342-43).
From Proto-Celtic *kan-o- 'to sing', PIE *kan- 'to sing' (IEW 525f., LIV²  342-43).

Based on the compound verb *ad-sed-o- 'to sit down', PIE *sed- 'to sit down' (LIV² 513-5), cf. the simplex verb Proto-Celtic *sed-o-, Matasović (2009, 325-26). A compound with the preverb *ad- is found only in Breton.

From Proto-Celtic *krok(ke)no- 'skin'.
"W points to the original *krokno-, while other languages show reflexes of *krokkeno-. A connection with PIE *sker- 'cut' (lEW 943) is difficult (*(s)kr-ok- does not look like a possible stem-shape). Thus, this word is probably a loanword from some non-IE language."

The Brittonic words are cognate with Old Irish nem 'sky'. There are several possible etymologies, some of which are also cited in Pokorny (315, 764) and LEIA N-8. 1. Cognate with 'cloud', cf. Old Indic nábhaḥ, Greek νέφος, Old Church Slavonic nebo.
2. From PIE *nem- 'zuteilen, to distribute, allot' (LIV² 453).
3. From PIE *nem- 'to bent' (LIV² 453f.).
The present cognate judgement adopts hypothesis 1.

The Iranian root *θang- ʿto pullʿ < *tʰang- < *tangʰ- belongs to *tengʰ- (thus better than *tʰengʰ- LIV²).

First attested in the Catholicon (1499). Brittonic verb based on Latin quiēscō, quiēscere 'to rest, to take a rest, to relax'.
Pre-Middle Breton borrowing.

From Proto-Celtic *bekko- 'small'. Cf. the verb PCl. *beg-o- 'break' from PIE *bʰeg- 'to break' (LIV² 66, IEW 114f.). 
Matasović considers a deverbal adjective with the semantic development 'broken into pieces' > 'small'. The underlying PIE form would be *bheg-ko-. Although this would yield PCelt. *bekko- regularly, the formational pattern is not typical for PIE.
First attested in the Catholicon (1499). Borrowed from Old French sentir (1080) from Latin sentire.

Derivation in -ed from MBr. mog, moug 'hearth', Cornish, Welsh mwg, MIr. much. From Proto-Celtic *muk-V- 'smoke', with unclear quantity of the root vowel. Perhaps connected with PIE *(s)meu̯g̑ʰ- 'smoke' (IEW 971), but the reflexes of this root are often irregular.

From Proto-Celtic *slimono- 'polished, smooth', cf. PIE *slei̯- 'smear (with grease). Olr. slemon, slemain [0] 'smooth, sleek, polished'. OW limnint [3p Pres.] 'polish', MW llyfn 'polished, smooth'. OBret. limn gl. lentum, MBret. di-leffn 'hard', MoBret. levn 'smooth'. Co.leven
Related to Middle French lincable and gascon linqua 'to glide'.

From Proto-Celtic *argyo- 'white' [Adj], 'snow' [Noun] and related to Proto-Celtic *arganto- 'silver' < PIE  *h₂erg̑-n̥t-o-, cf. IEW 64. Alternative etymology: Hamp 1974, GPC and Deshayes (2003: 218) would relate these words to Olr. arg 'drop' « *argo-), but this word is attested almost only in glossaries, its gender and stem-formation are unknown, and its meaning cannot easily be derived from the original meaning 'white'.
From Proto-Celtic *natrik- 'serpent', based on PIE *(s)n̥h₂-tr- 'water snake' (IEW 747), cf. *(s)neh₂- 'to swim' (LIV² 572).
Compound of the interrogative pe 'what' and MBr. particle (?) nac. CHECK DGVB 283
Same roots as Indo-Iranian *ā + *ay-, so no different cognate class
Suppletive comparative is probably originally cognate and can as well belong to *sed- as the positive forms, so they should be united rather than split.

Based on Proto-Celtic *sterā 'star', cf. PIE: *h₂stēr 'star' (IEW 1028)
OIr. ser is a hapax (it occurs in one of the archaic Leinster
eulogies), its gender is unknown; therefore, the PCelt. reconstruction is uncertain.

Based on Proto-Celtic *sterā 'star', cf. PIE: *h₂stēr 'star' (IEW 1028) OIr. ser is a hapax (it occurs in one of the archaic Leinster eulogies), its gender is unknown; therefore, the PCelt. reconstruction is uncertain.
Borrowed from Middle French esterquer 'to starch' (?), < Middle Dutch sterken 'to make stiff'.

From Proto-Celtic *magino- 'stone, place', cognate with Proto-Celtic *magos 'plain, field'. The Brittonic words are cognate with OIr. magen, magan ā, f 'place' (DIL maigen).
"W maen is not just any stone, but one 'having some speciality or a
particular use', according to GPC. The Olr. form in -a is a collective built from *magino-, like Lat. loca from locus. The attribution in IEW (709) to the root *meg̑h₂- 'great' is possible, cf. Skt. mahī́- 'earth' < *'the great one')."

From Proto-Celtic *efino- 'right, correct, equal' < PIE *h₁ep-(i)no- 'even' (IEW 505).
"Could these words be derived from PIE *h₁epi- 'on, by' with the suffix *-no-? The vowel *-i- could have been lost in Germanic through syncope. The type of formation would be parallel to PCelt. *efirom 'behind'.
From Proto-Celtic *sou̯k-n-o- 'to suck', cf. PIE *seu̯k̑- 'to suck' (IEW 1012, LIV² 539).

From Proto-Celtic *sāu̯ol- / *sūli- 'sun', cf. PIE *seh₂u̯ōl 'sun'
It appears that there was still an ablauting paradigm in PCelt., Nom. sg. *sāu̯ol, Gen. *sūl-os, from which Olr. súil was abstracted. Another possibility would be to start with *sh₂u̯ōl- > *saūl- (with the regular change of *ō > *ū in the final syllable), thence *sūl-.

From Proto-Celtic *su̯ed-o- 'swell', cf. PIE *su̯ei̯d- 'to sweat, to start sweating' (IEW 1043, LIV² 607). For the semantic development 'sweat' > 'swell' see KPV 609.

From *couuediff, compound co- + huezaff and nasalsation of auslaut.

From Proto-Celtic *snā- 'to swim', PIE *sneh₂- 'to swim, to bathe' (IEW 971f., LIV² 572). The Brittonic verbal nouns (W nawf, MoBret. neuff) are parallel to OIr. snám (m, u) 'swimming' < PCelt. *snāmu- < PIE *sn̥h₂-mu-.

From Proto-Celtic *snā- 'to swim', PIE *sneh₂- 'to swim, to bathe' (IEW 97lf., LIV² 572). The Brittonic verbal nouns (W nawf, MoBret. neuff) are parallel to OIr. snám (m, u) 'swimming' < PCelt. *snāmu- < PIE *sn̥h₂-mu-.

Given the three different words for 'wash' in Classical Greek, and the non-attestations of the other two (i.e. λούω, πλύνω) we cannot be confident this root was the most basic lexeme in Mycenaean Greek.

From Proto-Celtic *lusto- or *lustā-, cf. PIE *leu̯s- 'to detach oneself, to losen' (LIV² 374f., fn. 7).
Welsh llost f. seems to originate from *lustā-, OIr. los (m. o) from *lusto-. 
Schrijver (1995, 412) reconstructs a formation with *-st-, i.e. *lus-sto/eh₂-.

From Proto-Celtic *lusto- or *lustā-, cf. PIE *leu̯s- 'to detach oneself, to losen' (LIV² 374f., fn. 7). Welsh llost f. seems to originate from *lustā-, OIr. los (m. o) from *lusto-. Schrijver (1995, 412) reconstructs a formation with *-st-, i.e. *lus-sto/eh₂-.

From Late Proto-British msg. *hǝnnuɨθ/δ, fsg. *honnuɨθ/δ, neuter sg. and pl. *hǝnnɨθ/δ perhaps also neuter sg. *hǝnnuɨθ/δ. The first element *hǝnn- originates from *sondos (e.g. in MW hwnn msg.), the second element is *eisii̯o 'that there' >PBr. *ẹ̄hiδ > *uɨhɨδ > *uɨɨδ > *uɨδ (p. 70). The first element *sondos 'this' contains the acc.sg. of the demonstrative pronoun *so- and a element *-de-, i.e. *som-de > *sonde (p. 30).

From Proto-Celtic *tegu- 'thick' < PIE *tegu- 'thick' (IEW 1057). 
Reflexes of this PIE root are attested only in Celtic and Germanic.

Oir. mín 'tender, soft' from Proto-Celtic *mīno- < *miHno-, and W mwyn 'mild, tender, gentle', MoBret. moan 'tender, thin', OCo. muin 'thin' < Proto-Celtic *mēnV- < *mei̯HnV- (IEW 711f.). Alternatively from Proto-Celtic *moi̯ni- 'treasure, precious object', PIE *mei̯-n- 'exchange' (IEW 710) (Matasović p. 278f.). "The development of meaning in Breton and Cornish was from 'beautiful' to 'gracile' and (in Breton) 'thin'. The original meaning may have been '(precious) piece of property for exchange'."
From old divine name *ahura- mazdāh-; similarly in Khwarezmian and Sanglichi-Ishkashmi.

The Celtic form *tanau̯i̯o/ā- originates perhaps from *tn̥h₂-au̯-i(a)h₂, a derivative based on the form with full grade in the suffix *tanau̯- (if *-au̯- reflects *-eu̯-). Irish and Welsh show umlaut with *-i̯-, while the Breton and Cornish forms seem to represent *tanau̯o/ā- which could be identical with Greek ταναὀς. It is however more probably that it originates from a Celtic development starting in the feminine *tanau̯i̯ā > *tanau̯ā (Schrijver 1995, 262).

Verb based on Old Breton preteram 'to think', pritiri 'thought, reflexion, worry' and cognate with W, Corn. pryder 'anxiety, distress'.

-se originates from Proto-British *si̯o- or *sii̯o- < PIE *sio- and is cognate with Ved. syá, f. syā́ n. tyád.
The definite article Middle Breton an, Old Breton in originates from *sindos, f. *sindā. These forms have acquired pronominal inflection and are based on *sin-de. *sin-de contains the anaphoric pronoun *sin < *sim and the particle *-de-.
PIE *s(i)i̯ó- 'this', pronominal stem, deictic (proximal), singulare tantum
The cognacy judgement refers only to the first part of this discontinous marker, i.e. the definite article an < *sindos m., sindā- f. < *sin-de < *sim-de (cf. Schrijver 1997, 45, LIPP II 742).
The cognacy judgement refers only to the second part of this compound marker, i.e. -se.

From Proto-Celtic *me < PIE acc. sg. *(h₁)me, which ousted the old nom. sg. *(h₁)égoH. Old and Midddle Welsh reflect Late Proto-British *mi < *mī, while Middle and Modern Breton me and Middle Cornish my, me point to /mı/ < Late Proto-British *mɨ < Proto-British *mi. The development of these forms is related to those of the 2nd person Proto-Celtic *tū, which regulary became Proto-British *tȳ > *tī. This generated an analogical Proto-British nom. sg. *mū > *mȳ > *mi. The Proto-Celtic acc. sg. *me regularly became Proto-British *mi. Thus arose a PBr. system with nom. sg. *mī, *tī, acc. sg. *mi, *ti. Of these forms, Old Welsh generalized the former variant, Old South-West British the latter. A parallel development is found with the 2nd person pronouns.

Of these forms, Old Welsh generalized the former variant, Old South-West British the latter. A parallel development is found with the 2nd person pronouns.

Latin cremāre is probably a a denominative present. The word cannot be connected to a PIE root. The only possible cognate is the Celtic word for 'beer', PCl. *kormi- (e.g. Gaulish curmi, OIr. cuirm etc), but the alternation Latin *krem- vs. Celtic *korm- is unexplained.

Proto-Italic *gʷela-i̯e/o-, PIE *gʷelh₁-ie/o- 'to raise the arm, to throw' (LIV² 208). De Vaan suggests to come back to this etymology proposed by Müller (1926, 213), rejected by Walde-Hofmann. If the original meaning was 'to raise the arm', a shift to 'fly' is quite conceivable in the connection with birds.

From the PIE collocation / light-verb construction *gʷer(H)-dʰeh₁- 'to give news, to make known', i.e. *gʷer(H)- 'to consent' (LIV² 210f.) and *dʰeh₁- 'to put, to place, to make' (LIV² 136ff.). See also PIE *gʷerdʰ- 'to hear, to sound' (LIV² 187).

According to LIV² 352 from PIE ?*k⁽ʷ⁾erd- 'to hear'. The root could originate from collocation *kerH-dʰeh₁-, i.e. *kerH- 'to praise' (LIV² 353) and *dʰeh₁- 'to put, to place, to make' (LIV² 136ff.). This collocation was parallel to or influenced by the collocation *gʷer(H)-dʰeh₁- 'to give news, to make known' underlying Lithuanian girdėti 'to hear'. Although formally and semantically similar, the Lithuanian and Old Prussian verbs are not cognate.
From Proto-Italic Pit. *au̯izdi̯e/o- 'to hear', based on the collocation /light verb construction *h₂eu̯i(s) 'manifest' and *dʰeh₁- 'to put, to place, to make' (LIV² 136ff.).

From the Proto-Celtic noun *selgā 'hunt', cf. PIE *selg̑- 'send away, set loose' (LIV² 528-29, IEW 900f.).

OIr. fiad (m, u) 'wild animals, game', fiad 'uncultivated land' and fiadach 'hunt', Ogam VEDA-CUNAS, MW gwydd, OBret. guoid-och gl. aper, MBret. goez, MoBret. gouez, OCo. guit-fil gl. fera. From Proto-Germanic *barku- m., which adopted feminine gender in Low German and Dutch. Etymology unknown.

Probably with a reduplicated stem as in dìdis 'big, important'. Cognate with Latv. dižs 'big, noble, magnificent', but no other cognates. Commonly conntected with PIE *dei̯h₂- 'to light up' (LIV² 108, IEW 183f.), which is however problematic, as Winter's lengthening is lacking).
Secondary form from Attic Greek φῶς 'light'.
Anc.Gk. φῶς originally from PIE root *bʰeh₂- 'shine' as in Skt. bhā́ti 'lighten, shine'.
The etymological meaning is 'to knock, to bang'. The semantic development seems to be 'to knock, to bang'>'to fall with a noise'>'to fall'.

The word is derived from *sad- 'fruit orchard' which iteslf is not attested in the Polabian corpus. The etymology can suggest a more specified meaning than the standard Swadesh term. 'sodĕvaină' does not mean 'a single fruit' but it is a collective noun. In many Slavic languages two different words are used for a 'single fruit' in the most general meaning (which was taken for the lists) and for a 'mass of edible fruits'. Therefore it is better to exclude it.
Cognates of this lexeme in the other Slavic languages have a meaning 'herb(s)'.
Etymologically it is a diminutive from 'zaivăt' 'belly, stomach'.
Attested only once in a phrase 'hit him in the mouth'. It is not clear if it is really the Swadesh term.
Firstly, it is a German loanword. Secondly, it means 'to inhabit'.
The lexeme is attested only in the context of 'flax (seed)'. It is likely that the word is really restricted to the flax only (the same happened in Polish). So it should be exluded.
It is a substantive with the same root as in 'ostr-' but with a different suffix and a highly specified meaning. Added only as an interesting thing.
Firstly, it is a German loanword. Secondly, it is a verb for 'emitting or producing an odour'.
It is a verb for 'emitting or producing an odour'.
Attested in the meaning 'to split woods'.
The etymology suggest that it can be not a generic word for 'stick' but rather a term for a part of the 'flail'. However, it is not entirely clear.
It is attested in the meaning 'walking stick' only.
The etymological meaning, attested in the Polabian corpus too, is 'oak'. However, the compound 'jobťĕdǫb' 'apple tree' shows clearly that the general meaning 'tree' was really present.
It occurs only in a phrase 'blanťă zauzălaićă' 'shining worm' and it is not entirely clear if the substantive really had the generic meaning 'worm'.
"An Oriental Wanderwort, presumably of Iranian origin, cf. Arm. jag 'chick', NPers zaq 'cub'."

The history of the Slavic word(s) for 'shadow' is complicated and there are different hypotheses and versions of them. It is possible that we deal here with one single etymon with contaminations with other simmilar words and irregular taboo changes that gives three forms that can not be just put together without any additional hypotheses from phonetic reasons. It is also possible that we deal here with two or three independent etymona from the most deep etymology perspective. There can be a link to Greek 'σκία'.
From Middle English bi cause of 'by cause of'.

The history of the Slavic word(s) for 'shadow' is complicated and there are different hypotheses and versions of them. It is possible that we deal here with one single etymon with contaminations with other simmilar words and irregular taboo changes that gives three forms that can not be just put together without any additional hypotheses from phonetic reasons. It is also possible that we deal here with two or three independent etymona from the most deep etymology perspective. There can be a link to Greek 'σκία'.

Proto Slavic seems to have two synonyms for the meaning 'name': *jьmę, *jьmene and *měno, měna. Derksen puts their reflexes in modern Slavic languages together as reflexes of IE *h₁nḗh₃-mn̥  with any explanaition. Polish has (and had) both of them ('imię', 'miano') and this alone makes the assumption of a common etymology very doubtfull. There is no phonetic possibility to generate the Polish words from the single Proto-Slavic *jьmę, *jьmene (it is equally impossible to generate the Proto Slavic words from the single IE *h₁nḗh₃-mn̥  phonetically). Therefore Slavic/Polish etymologists keep *jьmę and *měno apart from each other (e.g. Boryś 2005). Upper Sorbian mjeno and Slovak meno, although superficially very similar to Polish miano, are reflexes of *jьmę (or, more precisely, of its forms).
The problem with Kashubian is that 'miono' can not be traced directly to Proto-Slavic *měno (we would expect here the same form as in Polish: **'miano'). The explanation is that the original *měno was contaminated by -e- from *jьmene.
For now the Kashubian word should be put into a separate cognate class. The problem should be, however, studied closer.

Generalized weak stem alternant *da- of PIE *deh₃- with initial fricative dh- from sandhi in the frequent position after the marker of the indirect object 3sg. *i (cf. l.c. 235).
s.v. manca 'mano sinistra'; mancu m. 'lato sinistra', adj. 'sinistro', esp. manu manca 'mano sinistra'.

The common prefixed variants zborë, dëborë, xborë, vdorë and bdorë support the origin in the verb bíe 'to fall', bjérr 'lose' < PIE *bʰerH-, based on the stem of the aorist, cf. Romanian zăpadă 'snow' <-- Slav *zapadъ 'fallen'.
vombicare in Calabria Media (Catanzaro); general Calabrian: vommicare, Std. Italian vomitare.
(s.v. shteg:) ík(i) Arb. Gr./It. ikënj < (extended) root *h₁ei̯-k- 'weg-, hingehen', cf. also shkoj.
Follows Demiraj and treats it as ultimately belonging to *h₁ei̯-.

To PIE *[h₁]ei̯- with -k- from the imperative and such forming an equation with Lith. eîk, eîki 'go!' and finding a parallel in Slav. *jьdǫ 'go' which might have generalized the imperative ending *-dhi as well.
zhur, shur 'gravel'. Borrowed from Lat. saburra 'sand ballast'.
njegull secondary from mjegull 'cloud', Proto Alb. *meg(u)la- ~ Grk. ὀμίχλη 'fog, mist', Lith. miglà 'id.', Slav. mъgla 'darkness, mist'.

Doubts the connection of mje(r)gull(ë) and simplex njeg, niég 'hazy weather' (attested elsewhere in Old Albanian) and compares Roman. negură 'fog' (which itself is treated as a loan from Albanian, nevertheless) and with potential indirect connection Avest. snaoδa- 'clouds', Lat. nūbēs 'fog, mist', Welsh nudd 'id.', though the sound correspence bears problems (PIE *dʰ vs. *g(ʷ)).
fjeta (also flétë, pl. flétëra) < Ital. foglietto 'A small piece of paper, a slip, a leaflet'
Proto Alb. *salwa- ~ Akt. sárva etc., with older literature.

(i) gjallë 'alive, vivid'; Arbëresh It./Gr., oldest literature gjéllë 'life, existence'. 
~ Skr. sárva-, Grk. ὅλος 'whole, entire', Lat. salvus 'safe, well, unharmed'.
Std.Alb. shalë 'saddle; inner side of thigh, pair of legs' borrowed from Lat. sella 'seat, saddle', thus in both meanings going back to the same source.
Std.Alb. shalë 'saddle; inner side of thigh, pair of legs' borrowed from Lat. sella 'seat, saddle', thus in both meanings going back to the same source.
PrAlb. *wada < *u̯odʰā- to root *u̯odʰ- 'to beat, break' with comparision to Slav. *tropa 'path' to *treapati 'to knock, beat'.

udhë 'way, road, track, approach; journey; route'. Loan from Greek ὁδός doubtful due the position of the accent. For semantic reasons best to be connected with Skr. váhati, Lat. vehō, NHG Weg; PrAlb. *uð- < PIE *ug̑ʰ-o-s/m and secondary transfer into fem. *ā-stems.
[Note: early formation and semantic split necessary since the root *u̯eg̑ʰ- is otherwise attested in Alb. vjedh 'to steal', the latter connection having been emphasized in Matzinger/Schumacher 2013:1008 again.]

Std.Alb. lis m. 'oak, high tree' borrowed from an ikavian South Slavic descendant of PrSlav. *lěsъ 'wood, forest, tree'
[Note that ikavian dialects have no direct connection to Albanian language areas.]
Notes only mask. lis, det. lísi, neuter pl. det. líst and narrower meaning 'oak tree'; transmitted via Serbian lijes 'timber; coffin'.

Discusses dialectal (North Geg) zgurdhë 'rectum' as formation in -dhë to (Geg) zgúer 'empty hole, orifice, vanum' and compares Alb. (esp. Geg) zgrof 'stomach' ~ gropë 'pit, hole'. Further etymology remains unclear.
[Though in another dialectal area, k/gufizë could be a similar formation with productive diminutive -izë to gufë 'cave; hollow (esp. in a trunk tree)', itself a prefixless variant of zgavër ~ zguer 'hole'].

Derivative in *-no- from root *gʷei̯H- 'to overpower' (~ Skt. jáyati).
[Note that *-no- does not derive verbs.]

Old verbal basis *zan ~ zen-, aor. *zon, ptc. *zan- [therefore -n- must be a part of the root].
*gʷ(ʰ)en- is possible for the anlaut but the the lowering of the vowel is unexpected.
The broad variety of meanings of the verb and its compounds as well as a couple of phonological possible developments make it hard to determine the root. They don't see any clear cognate within IE.
Notes the use as an adjective 'raging, wild' and thus treats it as an early borrowing from Slav. *bystrъ, f. *bystra 'quick'.
Calab.-Alb. ngë ~ nëngë, nëng, nuk, Sic.-Alb. ngë < Lat. nunquam 'never' and/or umquam 'ever'.
ndej ~ ndêj 'to stretch out, to spread' < *en-tenja ~ Grk. τείνω (ἐντείνω 'stretch out'), Skt.tanóti

nedj, ndêj; secondarily (dialectal South Tosk, Arbëresh Gr/It.) ndë(n)j with dialectal darkening of the vowel.
Demiraj notes the meanings 'ziehen, spannen; ausstrecken, ausbreiten', dep. 'jmdm. folgen, hinterherlaufen', intr. 'gehen nach, (um)ziehen nach'.
< *ten-i̯o-. Since root(e) is rare for jo-presents in Albanian it might be a younger formation. On the other hand, the number of different formations attested in Albanian could indicate a contamination of different old formations, cf. Grk. τανύω, τιταίνω, Lat. teneo, tendo.
Early Pr.Alb. *(an-) + ten-i̯e/o- ~ Grk. (ἐν-) + τείνω on a post-PIE level.
Loan < Lat. intelligere 'to perceive', cf. dialectal forms such as ndëgoj, dëlgonj, diligonj.

Old Alb. /gjegjetë/ consistently means 'hears' and therefore is most likely (with Klingenschmitt) < *seh₂g- 'to keep track, trace' (what also shows that the root which is otherwise attested in centum languages only contains a plain velar). Either < *sh₂g-é/ó- or *sh₂g-i̯é/ó- and therefore to be directly connected with Goth.(+) sakan and OIr. -saig ‘seeks, searches'.

[For vb. mbështét/s 'to stand, prop, lean, lay down':]
Obviously preverb n(ë) + pështes/t. Demiraj compares the latter with pështás/t 'to adjust, adapt' but sees it as a parallel formation only. Both share the root *sta-t- < *steh₂- with simplex shtat 'bodily frame; stature; stand' which has sometimes been treated as a loan from Latin, but without need.
[For vb. mbështet 'to stand, prop':]  < Pr.Alb. *ambhi-stata based on an adjective *stata < PIE *sth₂-tó- 'standing' ~ Skt. shtitá-, Grk. στατός.
grykë 'throat' > Pr.Alb. grīwīkā, related to IE *grīwā 'neck' ~ Skt. Av. grīvā, Latv. grĩva 'river mouth', Slav. *griva 'mane'; < root *gʷer- 'to swallow, eat'.

Follows Jokl and connects grýkë f., gurmáz m. 'neck' as well as zorrë 'intestine', ãngërr, ãngurrë f. 'guts', with ngrënë - the ptc. of ha 'to eat' (a similar same stem appears in aor. hëngra). Together with Skt. giráti 'to swallow' and Lat. vorō 'id.' it goes back to PIE *gʷerh₃-.
S.v. Khot. bulysa- 'long', to Av. bərəzant- 'high', BSogd. βrzʾk, βrz 'long', Waxī vərz, vorz 'long', Pašto ūẓ̌d, etc., from PIE *bʰerg̑ʰ-
cf. Pashto γūna 'hair (of the body), pore, colour (of the skin)'
Meaning and therefore cognacy of Vedic word dā́nu- not clear.
